    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ad, Ai-l, Aq, At, Av-w, Ay). The <i>Tuctoria greenei-Marsilea vestita</i> type (Barbour et al. 2007b) occurs in the northeastern Sacramento Valley region in one large playapool, and it shares <i>Chamaesyce hooveri</i> and <i>Plagiobothrys stipitatus</i> with some of the following types. This type appears related to the <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Downingia (bicornuta)</i> alliance based on species composition, regional distribution, and geomorphic surfaces. The other types identified by Barbour et al. occur in the Solano-Colusa pool region (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998). The <i>Atriplex persistens, Chamaesyce hooveri-Bolboschoenus maritimus,</i> and <i>Orcuttia pilosa</i> types occur at the Sacramento Wildlife Refuge. The <i>Neostapfia colusana-Malvella leprosa</i> type appears limited to Olcott Lake in Jepson Prairie, whereas the <i>Neostapfia colusana-Polypogon maritimus</i> and <i>Tuctoria mucronata</i> types occur within 12 km southeast of Davis on Department of Defense land. The latter type also occurs in the Jepson Prairie area. These types have a similar, but depauperate species makeup, including <i>Cressa truxillensis</i> and/or <i>Crypsis schoenoides;</i> however, each type differs in which rare plant species are present. Many stands dominated by <i>Cressa truxillensis</i> and/or <i>Distichlis spicata,</i> but lacking vernal pool diagnostic species, are also common in managed wetlands in the alkaline soils of the San Joaquin Valley in Kern National Wildlife Refuge.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-c, Bg, Bj). Stands occur in upper tidal salt marshes, including Ballona Wetlands in Los Angeles Co. (California Coastal Conservancy 2006) and Los Penaquitos Lagoon and Tijuana Estuary in San Diego Co. (Driver 2006, West and Cordrey 2003). These uncommon situations have not been sampled well. The full extent of this alliance is unknown, but the alliance appears limited to flat clayey areas, claypan vernal pools, and salt marshes. Many of these sites have been impacted by agriculture, development, and non-native plants. Other stands where the two species co-occur include alkaline mud plains along the Gulf of California (MacDougal 1904). Only with more sampling and analysis of similar vegetation will we understand the role of these stands in Californiaâ€™s vegetation.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
